1 repair provider and an original equipment manufacturer, including but not limited to the performance or
2 provision of warranty or recall repair work by an authorized repair provider on behalf of an original equipment
3 manufacturer and pursuant to the arrangement, except that a provision in the terms that purports to waive,
4 avoid, restrict, or limit the original equipment manufacturer's obligations to comply with [sections 1 through 4] is
5 void and unenforceable.
6 (2) An original equipment manufacturer or authorized repair provider is not liable for any damage
7 or injury to any agricultural equipment caused by an independent repair provider or owner that occurs during
8 the course of repair, diagnosis, or maintenance and is not attributable to the original equipment manufacturer or
9 authorized repair provider other than if the failure is attributable to design or manufacturing defects.
10 (3) Nothing in [sections 1 through 4] requires:
11 (a) a manufacturer to make available special documentation, tools, and parts that would disable or
12 override anti-theft security measures set by the owner of the product without the owners authorization;
13 (b) a manufacturer to sell a part if the part is no longer available to the manufacturer;
14 (c) a manufacturer to sell any service materials that are illegal to use under federal or state law; or
15 (d) a parts dealer from marking up goods over the wholesale price.
16
17 NEW SECTION. Section 5. Effective date. [This act] is effective January 1, 2026.
18
19 NEW SECTION. Section 6. Codification instruction. [Sections 1 through 4] are intended to be
20 codified as new part in Title 30, chapter 14, and the provisions of Title 30, chapter 14, apply to [sections 1
21 through 4].
22
23 NEW SECTION. Section 7. Contingent termination. [This act] terminates on the date that the
24 attorney general certifies to the code commissioner that the United States congress enacts federal legislation
25 establishing a right to repair agricultural equipment. [Sections 1 through 4] are repealed effective on the date
26 identified in the notice that the federal legislation is enacted or, if the notice does not specify that date, on the
27 date of the notice to the revisor of statutes.
